included.name: Anticipatory conditioning of spelling-to-sound translation
included.description:
College studentsâ pronunciations of initial c and g were examined in English words and nonwords, both monosyllables and polysyllables. Pronunciations were influenced by adjacent context â whether the following letter was e or i â and by long-distance context â whether the item contained a suffix or spelling pattern characteristic of Latinate words. Pronunciations were also influenced by whether students had studied a language such as French in which c and g are systematically fronted before those vowels. The findings were not well fit by either a dual-route or a single-route reading model. Although skilled readers were affected by the contextual patterns in the input, they did not use these patterns to the extent that would be expected given the patternsâ reliability in the English vocabulary. The results are discussed in
terms of the size of the window within which spelling-to-sound translation takes place and the nature of the units that are used.

included.name: He says, she says: Does voice affect usability?
included.publisher: Proceedings of the Human Factors and Ergonomics Society 56th Annual Meeting
included.description: Interactive voice response systems (IVRs) are ubiquitous user interfaces that allow customers to gather information and execute transactions. Because the entire user interaction is auditory-based, the voice used in the IVR is of high importance. Entities that field IVRs go to great lengths to select appropriate voices, usually on the basis of aesthetics of the voice, or on branding considerations. While much has been written on the usability of these IVR systems from the perspective of navigation, the impact of the voice on the usability of IVRs has not been well explored. Towards this end, we investigated the impact of voice personality and speaker gender on the usability of an interactive voice response system. Results suggest that voice characteristics can have an impact on the perceived usability of the system, with male voices resulting in higher usability metrics than female voices.

included.name: Improvement of a social gaming checkout user interface
included.publisher: Proceedings of the Human Factors and Ergonomics Society 56th Annual Meeting
included.description: Social games are utilizing virtual currency to increase the gaming experience as well as their bottom line. Users must progress through a checkout user interface in order to obtain this virtual currency, and the onus is placed on the development team, including the user researcher, to optimize this interface. Playfish recently performed testing on a new version of its checkout interface in one of its social games, Pet Society. It explored the usability and security of the interface, as well as the degree to which the interface integrated with Facebookâs checkout interface. While current spenders rated security quite low due to past personal and second-hand experiences, non-spendersâ ratings were not yet sullied by a negative checkout experience. Therefore, improvement to the interface, particularly in the security domain, has the ability to increase new usersâ perceptions when purchasing virtual currency, which may increase the number of microtransactions moving forward.

included.name: Increasing accuracy of video quality ratings through direction of attention and training
included.description: This paper describes the results of two studies undertaken to better understand the strong positive relationship between the content of a video clip and viewers' subjective ratings of the video quality of that clip. Experiment 1 evaluated the effect of training on video quality ratings. Experiment 2 assessed the impact of attention in these assessments. Experiment 1 showed that training participants on video quality assessment techniques removed viewers' heuristic reliance on affect while increasing accuracy. Experiment 2 demonstrated that participants' video quality ratings could also be improved by directing their focus of attention. Focusing viewers on quality did not show a moderation of the relationship between content immersion and video quality, as participants maintained high levels of content immersion even when focusing on video quality. Because training and attention increased quality rating accuracy, they could be utilized in video quality testing to improve the viewer feedback received.

included.name: Pogo Chat
included.publisher: Cases on Usability Engineering: Design and Development of Digital Products/IGI Global
included.description: Pogo.com, an Electronic Arts (EA) casual gaming website, has over 150 games. The older, timeless games, around 610 horizontal pixels, are neighbored by an online group chat window which allows players to communicate during gameplay. Newer games do not have the same size constraints, some as wide as 760 horizontal pixels. These newer games originally lacked a chat window; however, the feedback from Pogo users was clear â they wanted the ability to chat. This paper will focus on the iterative usability testing utilized in determining if and how chat should be added into these new games on Pogo. The chat solutions as well as some challenges faced in reaching these solutions are discussed. While players wanted a chat window in all games, they did not want it to interfere with their game play. There was a preference for multiple chat solutions depending on the size of the game brick.

included.name: The impact of voice characteristics on user response in an interactive voice response system
included.description: System voice within interactive voice response systems (IVRs) was investigated in order to determine if voice impacts a userâs input responses. In a medical setting, it is possible that a particular voice personality and/or gender may induce more or less disclosure, thus driving a patient to relay more or less sensitive information. In the IVR setting, one could determine this via examination of a userâs button-press responses. In this study, a male and female voice personality expressing an upbeat, professional, and sympathetic personality recorded a script for a medical IVR. Users were randomly assigned to one of these voice personalities when completing a health survey over that IVR. It was found that disclosure rates were not affected by the type of voice heard, nor did they differ by user gender. Additionally, disclosure was higher on the IVR version of the health survey than on a web-based version, further recognizing the privacy offered by IVRs. These findings indicate that designers of IVRs may not have to put additional effort into the selection of voice talent and can instead focus on the design of the IVR, itself.

included.name: Preferences for chat in casual games
included.description: Exploring how iterative testing enhances usability at Pogo through a description of Pogo's team structure -- how does research fit in to the UX process? In order to highlight the place of research throughout the entire lifecycle of a product, and its influence on design decisions, two case studies are utilized. The first case study discusses a facelift to chat on Pogo.com for games that lacked chat. The second discusses how chat was implemented in mobile games.

included.name: Voice personalities inducing trust and satisfaction in a medical interactive voice response system
included.publisher: Proceedings of the Human Factors and Ergonomics Society 53rd Annual Meeting
included.description: Verbal and non-verbal behaviors that contribute to trust and satisfaction in the patient-physician relationship have typically been investigated in face-to-face interactions between patient and physician. However, it is becoming more common for physicians to administer surveys over interactive voice response systems (IVRs). In this context, patient trust and satisfaction must still be maintained in order to insure accurate disclosure on the surveys. This paper describes the results of research in which we investigated if individualsâ perceptions of trust and satisfaction are affected through voice, alone. When considering voice in the absence of non-verbal cues, a sympathetic voice was more liked and trusted than a professional voice, which was more liked and trusted than an upbeat voice. It was also found that trust can be moderated by the gender of the voice presented in an IVR, with females reporting higher trust for professional voices than do males.
